               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1470" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1470" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1470" type="surname" value="LOCKWOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1470" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN LOCKWOOD</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 8th of Oct., the prisoner was in Mr. Bay<lb></lb>field's employ—two lads were also in the service—we had a pledge made on the 1st of Dec., 1842, of a watch and guard, in the name of William Pinkney, of Grove-place—that watch was afterwards applied for and missed—the prisoner left on the 14th of Oct.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1471" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1471" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1471" type="surname" value="PINKNEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1471" type="given" value="JOHN JAMES"></interp>JOHN JAMES PINKNEY</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">general dealer, Grove-place, Lambeth.</hi> This watch and guard is mine—Ipledged it at Mr. Bayfield's on the 1st of Dec., 1842, in the name of Pinkney, of Grove-place, for 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.,—Iapplied to take it oat at the latter end of November last year—Iam quite sure this is the watch.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> How do you know it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> By the number 20, 229 and the maker's name, Duchesne.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1472" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1472" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1472" type="surname" value="GOODWIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1472" type="given" value="MARY CHRISTINA"></interp>MARY CHRISTINA GOODWIN</persName>
                  </hi>. Iknow the prisoner—Ipledged a watch at his desire at Mr. Jones's for 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;, on the 8th of Oct. in the name of Clyne, and on the 11th got 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. more on it—Isent the ticket to the prisoner in sletter—this watch is a great deal like the one, and Ibelieve it to be the same.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did you pledge it at my request? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, you gave it to me—Icannot say that Iever saw you with it before Ipledged it—Icannot wear this is the watch—is is a great deal like it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Charles Cripps.</hi> Iam in the service pf Thomas Jones, a pawnbroker, in St. George's-circus. On the 9th of Oct. a watch without a glass, and a guard, were pledged in the name of Clyne—it was afterwards redeemed by the prisoner—he employed me to get a glass to it—he pledged it again himself—it was again redeemed on the morning of the 23rd of Jan. but not by him—some other property of his was redeemed at the same time to the amount of 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and was paid for all in silver.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Was that watch ever pledged at your shop before Goodwin pledged it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, Iam sure of that.</p>
