               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I expected to have witnesses to prove I had the watch a long time prior to entering Mr. Bay field's service; Pinkn ey has been shown the watch before, so as to know the number.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1474" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1474" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1474" type="surname" value="PINKNEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1474" type="given" value="JOHN JAS"></interp>JOHN JAS. PINKNEY</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I had not noticed the number before I lost it, but I went to Mr. Carter, the chronometer maker, on Cornhill, who cleaned it for me three years ago, and had it in his hands two or three times, and he gave me the number from his book—they always take the numbers of the watches they clean—I have had it seven years, and am quite positive it is mine—I can recognize it from the dial, and from having it in use so many years, independent of the number.</p>
